{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472450"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:58:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1457"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.04,0,0.01,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109371"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91739"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"370"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2067"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3251"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35696"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109371"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 6-year-old girl is brought into the Emergency Department by her mother with a 3-day history of hoarseness of voice and a barking cough. Her mother reports a mild fever over this period but denies any drooling. The girl\u0027s medical history is unremarkable and she is up to date with her vaccinations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she does not appear toxic and there is mildly increased work of breathing with audible stridor. An X-ray is performed and shows the following: (image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Croup","Foreign body","Upper lobe pneumonia","Diphtheria","Epiglottitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical picture and radiograph are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Ecroup\u003C/strong\u003E. The image shows the classic \u0027steeple sign\u0027 where there is tracheal narrowing in a graduated fashion - more marked superiorly - that is supposed to look like a church steeple. Croup, also known as laryngotracheobronchitis, is a viral infection of the upper airway and typically presents with a characteristic \u0027barking\u0027 cough, stridor, hoarseness and dyspnoea. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no \u003Cstrong\u003Eforeign body\u003C/strong\u003E present on the X-ray, and there is no consolidation to suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E, Whilst a foreign body would most likely be lodged in the upper airways, this diagnosis cannot be completely ruled out, as the chest X-ray is only showing part of the chest. The scenario fits well for croup and it should be understood that when the diagnosis is clear-cut on clinical grounds, an X-ray is superfluous.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiptheria\u003C/strong\u003E was historically a cause of croup; although, is now rare with routine vaccination. Approximately 75% of croup is caused by the \u003Cem\u003Eparainfluenza \u003C/em\u003Evirus\u003Cem\u003E, \u003C/em\u003Ewith the remainder caused by influenza, adenovirus and respiratory syncytial virus. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAssessment of severity is important in a suspected case of croup, while an assessment of toxicity is important in ruling out other differentials. If a child appears overtly toxic, it should raise suspicion for \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiglottitis\u003C/strong\u003E, an emergency requiring urgent hospital admission and airway support, and is caused by the vaccine preventable Haemophilus Influenzae type b. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA child with mild severity croup will not have stridor at rest, and will not show any signs of increased work of breathing. Moderate severity croup will have stridor at rest, as well as tachycardia, while severe and life-threatening croup will have increased work of breathing to the point of being unable to speak with confusion and drowsiness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMild and moderate severity croup may be managed in the community with monitoring. Treatment for croup includes oral steroids (prednisolone or dexamethasone) which has been shown to improve symptoms, reduce admission rates and length of hospitalisation in all severities of croup. The addition of nebulised adrenaline is recommended for moderate to severe croup. This is used to decrease airway inflammation whilst the steroids start to take effect.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Steeple sign on X-ray is a classic sign of croup.","Majority of croup cases are caused by parainfluenza infection."],"references":["Matsuura H, Shimanouchi Y. Steeple sign and acute laryngotracheobronchitis. QJM: An International Journal of Medicine. 2017;110(11):767-. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29025139/","Rajapaksa S, Starr M. Croup Assessment and management. Australian Family Physician. 2010;39:280-2. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20485713/","Smith DK, McDermott AJ, Sullivan JF. Croup: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2018;97(9):575-80. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29763253/","Croup (Laryngotracheobronchitis). The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Updated September 2024. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/croup_laryngotracheobronchitis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91739"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1872"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1872"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e6891a5b-15da-49b0-95f2-d873d61f3ef6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e6891a5b-15da-49b0-95f2-d873d61f3ef6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":636,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91739"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-20T19:11:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-20T19:11:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109371"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,